    "group": "PLACES / PHENOMENA",
    "raw": "# Boundary Research Institute\n\nFounded in **884**, the Boundary Research Institute is an intergovernmental research body created to study, contain, and exploit the region designated [[The Boundary|De Râne]]. It was established by a multinational group of scientists, including [[Director Sabine Reisz]], with the support of the Virelsk government and a network of multinational corporate backers whose interests range from materials research to information systems.\n\nThe Institute's official mandate is containment, forecasting, and regional study. Its practical work is larger: monitoring the edge, managing the cordon with Virelsk authorities, recovering what the Boundary pushes out after a Stilling, processing recovered material and altered persons, and developing technologies from Boundary-derived biological material.\n\n## Founding\n\nThe Institute was formed after the Boundary's appearance made ordinary national response insufficient. Virelsk retained territorial authority, but admitted the Institute under mandate because the phenomenon exceeded state capacity and because secrecy required a controlled, non-public structure. Reisz was part of the founding scientific group and became the Institute's director.\n\nCorporate support entered early. The public explanation is logistics and research funding. The private explanation is access: the Boundary produces materials and altered information effects no external laboratory can reproduce.\n\n## Mandate\n\nThe Institute holds three stated responsibilities:\n\n- Containment of De Râne and management of information about it.\n- Forecasting and response to Stillings, including post-swell recovery.\n- Study of anomalous materials, organisms, sites, and altered persons.\n\nIts unstated priority is the reproduction of Boundary effects without fatal exposure, especially where altered persons and nonlocal information are concerned.\n\n## Installations\n\nThe Institute works the region through a ring of monitoring stations, bunker-laboratories, and the principal interior installation at [[Breisk]]. [[Station 9]] sits closest to the deep and serves as a high-risk early-warning point. Breisk handles research, forecasting, post-swell collection, and the processing facility for recovered material and persons.\n\n## Security\n\nInstitute security is split between two arms:\n\n- **Perimeter Security Element** — field, edge, escort, recovery work, and engagements with [[Rânesk]].\n- **Containment Security Detachment** — cordon control, custody of recovered persons, Breisk security, and coordination with Virelsk authorities.\n\nThe Institute's public posture is containment and secrecy. Its operational posture is extraction, study, and denial.\n\n## Research Programs\n\nInstitute research begins with the Boundary's ecology: organisms that do not decay, organisms caught in time, mirror-growth, stillness sites, and other phenomena that express the region's law. The material cut from these organisms is used in Institute field technology and experimental systems.\n\nAltered persons are the Institute's highest-value output. Survivors of deep exposure are classified under Nonlocal Integration Syndrome, though [[Rânesk]] rejects this framing and names them Naarsken. The Institute cannot reproduce the effect without killing most subjects.\n\n## Computer Program\n\nThe deepest Institute program is informational. The working theory is temporal nonlocality: inside the Boundary, past, present, and future are not reliably held apart. The Institute's experimental computer systems attempt to exploit that condition.\n\nThe furthest-developed system is the **Chronological Tunneling Array**, built from Boundary-derived material. It is not treated as a faster computer, but as a machine that receives information out of chronological order. Logged runs have returned correct outputs before the calculations that should have produced them were complete.\n\nThe long objective is an atemporal information network: a system that can transmit or retrieve information independent of ordinary sequence. Whether the Boundary creates this effect or only opens onto it remains unresolved.\n",
