    "raw": "A border town built half inside the Boundary itself — the line runs through it, so part of the town stands in the Threshold and part stands out. Its people are held there under government lockdown, unable to leave. Where [[Ime Baardo]] and [[Senn Baardo]] are from.\n\n**Why no one leaves.** When the Boundary appeared ~15 years ago, some of Eirskel got out to **the Outside** — the ordinary country beyond the cordon. The Boundary's phenomena followed them: a person it has touched never fully leaves it, because a place with no center holds no *here* apart from *there*, and the body crosses the edge while the door stays open. Hushes thinned the air of distant streets, pools stood in strangers' cellars, people went too still and did not come back. So the government drew the cordon and holds it. No one goes **beyond the line**. The official reason is containment and secrecy; the real one is that every person raised against the Boundary is a way *in*, and the only way to watch the doors is to keep them all in one town. See [[The Boundary#Spatial nonlocality — the cordon and the open door]].\n",
