    "group": "PLACES / PHENOMENA",
    "raw": "# Naarsken\n\nSee also: [[The Boundary#The un-named — NIS and the Naarsken]].\n\n**Naarsken** is the [[Rânesk]] name for people the Institute classifies as suffering from **Nonlocal Integration Syndrome (NIS)**.\n\nThe Institute reads NIS as pathology: total loss of personal identity, near-total autobiographical erasure, persistent muttering, and the production of an untranslated language. Under instruments, the survivor's neurological activity is too high for the vacancy it wears. They recognise no one and recall nothing, yet keep doing things that imply access to information no ordinary sense delivered.\n\nRânesk rejects that framing. To the cult, the survivors are **Naarsken** — *naam*, name, self; *sken*, one who has been altered: those whose names have been taken away. It is un-naming made doctrine. Where the Institute reads damage, Rânesk reads transparency: the false self stripped, the Threshold speaking straight through the body.\n\nThis makes every Naarsken a contested person. Institute recovery teams pursue NIS subjects for custody and study. Rânesk hunts the Naarsken to shelter them, and some factions deliberately walk people into the Boundary to make more. Armed contests over individual survivors are on record.\n\n[[Ime Baardo]] is the exception that troubles both systems. She was caught in the kind of deep event that should have hollowed her into a Naarsken, but did not present with standard NIS. She lost memory without losing identity, language, personality, or ordinary function.\n",
