    "raw": "# Rânesk\n\n*The cult that worships the Boundary, which it calls **The Threshold**.*\n\nProject: [[The Space Between Names|The Space Between Names]]\n\n> The metaphysics live in [[The Boundary]]; this note is the faction. For un-naming, the Naarsken, and what a Listener is, read there.\n\n## What it is\n\nA young cult, about seven years old, that lives inside the Boundary — the deep is its home ground, where the institute will not follow. It holds the Boundary to be not a hazard but a presence: **The Threshold**, which speaks. Where the institute reads the un-named survivor as damage, Rânesk reads transparency — the false self stripped away and the Threshold speaking straight through the body. The survivors are sacred to it: the **Naarsken**, whose muttering is not a symptom but the sacred tongue. Rânesk shelters the Naarsken the institute would study, and the two collide over them — recovery teams against adherents, abduction, armed engagements over a vacant survivor neither side will leave to the other. Some factions go further and walk the living into the Boundary on purpose, to make more, holding that every Naarsken near deepens the Listener's reach.\n\n## Origin and succession\n\nNo line of holy fathers — Rânesk is too young. It has a founder, **Joren Vask**, and now [[Senn Baardo|Senn]], and nothing in between. Vask leaned over a still pool, saw his own face, and called it a god's gaze; he believed the Threshold *chose* him, and that belief is what carried him far enough into the deep to die — in the same deep Stilling that un-named [[Ime Baardo|Ime]]. Senn reads that death not as warning but as inheritance: the Threshold, finished with the first man, now choosing him. He is the second man to mistake the mirror, and the first to do it knowingly enough that it might be called a lie. The cult is too young to have learned what its own short history already proves — that no one is chosen, that the seat passes to whoever survives the last man's projection.\n\nSince the Stilling that took the founder and the Listener in the same moment, the cult has quietly reoriented around Senn's refusal to believe Ime dead. He drives it harder than the founder did — deeper expeditions, higher demands, the Threshold pressed for an answer.\n\n## How it takes people\n\nRecruitment runs in three movements, and the Boundary does most of the work.\n\n**The whisper.** Some come because they heard a rumour and wanted to belong. Some come because the Boundary is genuinely reaching them — the open door of spatial nonlocality, the pull on the already-touched (see [[The Boundary]]) — and they have no word for what they feel. Rânesk names both the same way: *the Threshold is calling you.* It watches the [[Vaarden|pilgrims]] and marks the ones who weep instead of run.\n\n**The belonging.** What it offers the unmoored is total and immediate — a place, a name inside the cult, a people. The grieving and the lost, the ones with nothing to go back to, are met first with warmth, then with isolation, then with the long nights in the sacred tongue. Ordinary coercive love, dressed as homecoming.\n\n**The point of no return.** Then they are taken deep. Real exposure does real things to a mind — dread, awe, the self thinning out — and every one of those states is named *the Threshold choosing you.* By the time the recruit surfaces they are past the cordon's screen: too touched to be passed back to the Outside, unable to go home. Belonging is no longer being offered. It is the only thing left. Rânesk does not need to break a person when the Boundary will do it and the cordon will keep them.\n\nThis is why the cult preys so well on exactly the wound the book turns on — [[Senn Baardo|Senn]]'s own, [[Ime Baardo|Ime]]'s own: the fear of being left, and the inability to refuse the only thing that ever stayed.\n\n## Making Naarsken — the guide's betrayal\n\nThe three movements above gather the willing. The Naarsken are made another way, and it is the thing the [[Vaarden]] elders most hate Rânesk for. Movement inside the Boundary needs a guide — someone who knows where the deep begins and where the stone runs deep enough to shelter. A Rânesk member takes that role: offers to lead a pilgrim or a delver in, and is trusted, because nothing about him gives the lie until the moment it matters. Then the hush comes, and the guide does not lead them to shelter. He bars them from the Down, or he has already walked them out past the band where any stone is deep enough, and he leaves. The Stilling does the rest.\n\nMost who are left to it die — survival runs under one in ten. Rânesk accepts the ratio: the dead feed the Threshold, and the rare survivor comes out un-named, a Naarsken, which to the cult is the holiest thing there is. A guide who can be trusted absolutely until the instant he cannot is the cult's most effective instrument — and the reason no careful person in Vaarden takes a guide whose face they do not already know.\n\n## Standing in Vaarden — cold war\n\nRânesk surfaces in [[Vaarden]] to trade and resupply, and it is not welcome there. The town's three elders keep people alive; Rânesk gives people to the deep, and walks pilgrims and delvers into it to make more Naarsken. To the elders that is a death cult thinning their own. It has come to blows. They cannot expel it — Rânesk holds the deep that Vaarden depends on — so it stays a standoff, always one incident from worse: the cult kept to the margins, recruiting in whispers, tolerated exactly as far as the trade requires and no further. And it keeps **spies** among the townsfolk — members posing as delvers, hunters, and guides, who mark the unmoored and set the betrayals up. The elders know the spies are there. They cannot always say who, which is its own kind of poison in a town that runs on knowing whom to trust at your back in the dark.\n\n*(Keep the mystery: whether the Threshold calls anyone at all, or whether Rânesk only names a pull the Boundary produces in everyone who comes near, is never resolved. The cult's certainty is the point, not the proof.)*\n",
