    "raw": "# Vaarden\n\n*The last stable foothold before the deep.*\n\nProject: [[The Space Between Names|The Space Between Names]]\n\nA shantytown inside the Boundary — the furthest in a person can still live. Not the edge (that is the institute's, and the cordon's) and not the deep (that is lethal, and [[Rânesk]]'s home ground). Vaarden sits in the middle band, on the threshold of survivability: the last place a Stilling can be ridden out, and so the last place anyone builds.\n\n## Why it holds\n\nVaarden is built on an old works that predates the Boundary — a quarry and its shafts cut into the volcanic rock, broken through in places into the lava tubes beneath, so that the refuge is part dug and part natural: deep galleries of basalt that run down out of the light. Two things follow from that stone, and between them they are the whole reason the town exists:\n\n- **A Stilling can be survived here.** Deep enough under rock, the field thins to something an edge-dweller would recognise: lethal in the open, survivable below. Further in, toward the deep, no stone goes deep enough — there you do not ride out a Stilling, you become it. Vaarden marks the line where that stops being true.\n- **The stone does not move.** When the interior resets after a Stilling, paths shift and the surface rearranges, but the pit and the shafts stay where they are — a fixed point in a place that has none. The site persists even when everything built on it does not.\n\nSo Vaarden is \"stable\" only the way a tide-line is stable. The refuge holds; the town on top of it does not. The hush comes, the warning runs through the shanties, and everyone goes **down** into the old workings to wait it out. They climb back into a place subtly rearranged and rebuild what the Stilling moved. Nothing on the surface is ever quite finished. That is why it is a shantytown and not a town — not poverty exactly, but impermanence written into the building of it.\n\n**Warning.** The hush reaches Vaarden as it reaches everywhere: birds gone, wind dropped, sound thinning. Instruments bought off the institute register the drop; the sensitive feel it sooner and deeper. A bell, a relayed cry, and the descent begins. Minutes, no more. *(See the hush, in [[The Boundary]] under \"The Stilling.\")*\n\n## Who washes up here\n\nVaarden is where everyone who works the inside converges — and where a good many of them are stranded. The cordon screens on the way *out*: brief, shallow exposure clears, but the deep- or long-touched cannot pass back to the Outside, the same open-door law that seals [[Eirskel]], applied one body at a time. The deeply changed have nowhere out. They collect here.\n\n- **[[Rânesk]]** — the cult lives within; the deep is theirs. Vaarden is where they surface to trade, resupply, and watch who has just arrived.\n- **Hunters** — they work the creature trade and the bounty. They take the benign Boundary organisms for their parts (the biological and structural material the institute's tech, the Array among it, is cut from), and they hunt the **Naarsken** for the price on a living survivor. Some are contracted to edge-station buyers; some freelance and sell to whoever pays.\n- **The institute, at arm's length** — no flag flies in Vaarden. But its buyers take the parts, its bounties price the Naarsken, and the hunters cash out at an edge station that asks no questions. The institute works the edge and reaches the middle through other people's hands.\n- **Delvers** — the unsanctioned. They slip the cordon to find what sells and carry it back out, while they still can. The same trade that killed [[Ime Baardo|Ime]] and [[Senn Baardo|Senn]]'s parents, grown into a profession.\n- **Pilgrims** — outsiders who come to stand in it. Some for the thrill, some because the Boundary calls them and they have no word for it. Rânesk watches the pilgrims: the ones who weep instead of run, it keeps. Tourism is the cult's recruiting ground.\n\n## Who keeps order\n\nNo government will admit Vaarden exists, so it keeps itself, and has settled on three old-timers — no title between them, no vote, only the authority of having survived longest. Each holds one pillar of staying alive:\n\n- **The one who runs the Down.** Keeper of the shelter and the descent — who goes below when the hush comes, in what order, how the space is shared, how long they wait. In the few minutes a Stilling allows, his word is the only law that matters. It is also the office [[Rânesk]] most threatens: a man barred from the Down, or led away from it, is a man the Stilling takes.\n- **The one who keeps the peace.** Arbiter of trade and disputes — what a creature-part is worth, whose claim is whose, what is done about the delver who knifed another over a find. The nearest thing Vaarden has to a court.\n- **The old guide.** The one who reads the interior — which paths the last Stilling moved, where the deep begins now, what came up that shouldn't have. Vaarden trusts its footing to him, which is exactly why a *false* guide is so dangerous a thing.\n\nBy reputation the three are chill: slow to anger, hard to rattle, men who have seen the worst the Boundary does and stopped performing fear about it. What they are not chill about is Rânesk.\n\n**Cold war with Rânesk.** The elders keep people alive; the cult gives people to the deep. Rânesk surfaces to trade and the elders allow it, because Rânesk holds the deep Vaarden cannot do without — but it has come to blows, and they cannot expel it without losing the deep. So it stays a standoff, always one incident from worse. The standing grievance is the recruiting in the margins, and worse than recruiting: **Rânesk keeps spies in Vaarden** — members posing as delvers, hunters, ordinary guides — who mark the pilgrims and the unmoored and set up what comes next. The elders know the spies are there and cannot always tell who. See [[Rânesk]] for the betrayal itself.\n\n## To develop\n\n- The old mineworks: its name, what was cut from it, who worked it before the Boundary came.\n- The three elders: names, faces, and which of them, if any, has a private accommodation with Rânesk despite the cold war.\n- Vaarden in the plot: it is Rânesk's surfacing-point, so it is plausibly where [[Senn Baardo|Senn]]'s search runs through.\n",
